    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Calamus parvifructus improperly include experiencing nausea, seizures, developing psychosis, and suffering liver damage. This is due to the presence of a compound called asarin, which is toxic and can cause adverse reactions. When ingested in large amounts or for extended periods, asarin can disrupt normal brain function, leading to seizures and psychosis. The liver damage is attributed to the plant's ability to interfere with the body's detoxification processes, causing a buildup of toxins that can lead to liver failure. Ingesting Calamus parvifructus without proper guidance and supervision can exacerbate these side effects, resulting in severe health complications.",
    "uses": "Calamus parvifructus has been traditionally used in Southeast Asian medicine, particularly in Malaysia and Indonesia, for its purported medicinal properties. Its rhizome is used to treat various health issues, including digestive problems and fever. The plant is also believed to have anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties. Additionally, Calamus parvifructus is used to alleviate symptoms of cough and cold. More research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of using Calamus parvifructus as a medicinal herb.",
    "taxonomy": "Calamus parvifructus is a species of plant in the family Acoraceae. It is a type of calamus or sweet flag, a group of plants that are commonly found in tropical and subtropical regions. The plant is closely related to other species within the same family, such as Calamus rotang and Calamus manan. Calamus parvifructus is often used in traditional medicine, particularly in Southeast Asia, where it is valued for its potential health benefits. The classification of Calamus parvifructus is further supported by its unique characteristics and physical features, which distinguish it from other species within the Acoraceae family.",
    "benefits": "Calamus parvifructus is known for its potential health benefits, particularly in traditional medicine. It is believed to possess anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, which may help in reducing inflammation and protecting against cell damage. The plant may also have antimicrobial and antifungal activities, making it useful in treating infections and promoting wound healing. Additionally, Calamus parvifructus is thought to have a positive effect on digestion and may be used to alleviate symptoms of diarrhea and other gastrointestinal issues. Further research is necessary to fully understand the plant's health benefits and potential applications.",
    "parts": "Calamus parvifructus is a plant species that is primarily used in traditional medicine, and its medicinal parts are its rhizomes and roots. These rhizomes are harvested and dried for use in various medicinal preparations. The plant's rhizomes are valued for their anti-inflammatory and antiseptic properties. The roots of Calamus parvifructus are also used in traditional remedies to treat various ailments. The rhizomes and roots of the plant have been used in traditional medicine for their potential health benefits.",
    "intro": "Calamus parvifructus, also known as Smilax ornata, is a plant species in the Smilacaceae family that is native to tropical Asia. The health benefits of Calamus parvifructus include its potential to aid in digestion, reduce inflammation, and exhibit antimicrobial properties, making it a popular herbal remedy for various gastrointestinal issues and infections. The bioactive constituents of Calamus parvifructus include sesquiterpenes, flavonoids, and phenolic acids, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. In traditional medicine, Calamus parvifructus is often used to prepare herbal teas, decoctions, and tinctures, which are commonly used to treat digestive problems and promote overall well-being."
